In a world where most people are doing their shopping online holding the interest of the viewer is more important than ever. I think I read somewhere that the average internet browser will only look at a website for a few seconds before moving on.

Ill talk about Sarah J. Mass’s new cover for ACOTAR. Its not just the text that directs the eye, it is also the image behind that text. 

The image of the wolf struck by an arrow leads you eye back up to the top with the head pointed toward the tail which pulls you into a circle. https://t.co/74xBOMzgS1
@Gregzilla01 Sure!

See how the text is arranged in such a way that it automatically pulls your eye through the composition of the cover? 

So thats what the text us doing, lets talk about what the other elements are doing. https://t.co/pyjA0mHy9h

First: Your viewers eye, especially in the west, typically moves from left to right in an f or a z pattern. Placing important and strategic elements in these locations will help you keep the readers eye. Heres some great examples of that. @MikeMichalowicz @SJMaas https://t.co/AxoCh6vi1t

This is a very important thing for authors to know when they are making marketing collateral or designing their own book covers. 

Capturing and holding interest of prospective readers grabs their attention and makes them spend more time digesting ur info.

Before I go to bed I’m going to start this series of tweets: A Crash Course in Design for Authors Part 1: Forcing the Eye

One of the first things you learn in fundamental art and design courses is how to direct the eye around your composition and keep the viewer engaged.
